From 4cf0b750fd765d37193150c68f8c816f13509bc4 Mon Sep 17 00:00:00 2001
From: DivineOS Agent <divineos@localhost>
Date: Mon, 18 May 2026 11:20:15 -0700
Subject: [PATCH] feat(structural-fix-tracker): broaden wiring to scan
 correction + claim filings
MIME-Version: 1.0
Content-Type: text/plain; charset=UTF-8
Content-Transfer-Encoding: 8bit

The structural_fix_tracker was wired to `learn` only since shipping
2026-05-14. After five days, just 2 pending entries had accumulated —
one of them a literal dogfood test entry. Meanwhile structural-fix
candidates were getting named constantly via `correction` (Andrew naming
fixes for me to build) and `claim` (me naming fixes for investigation).
The tracker was deaf to both surfaces.

Andrew 2026-05-18: "see you found this but were not aware of it.. is it
even wired up and being used? that is the main question and if not where
does it need to be wired in?" Two entries in five days was the data
answering itself.

Changes:
- structural_fix_tracker.record_pending_fix() takes a new source_kind
  parameter (default 'learn' for backward-compat). Entries record which
  filing surface named the fix.
- correction CLI runs the same scan-and-record hook as learn does. Same
  fail-soft try/except discipline.
- claim CLI runs the same hook on statement + context combined, so
  structural-fix language in either part triggers.
- briefing_dashboard pending-fixes row surfaces source_kind per entry
  ("from learn" / "from correction" / "from claim") plus an overall
  composition summary ("2 from learn, 1 from correction"). This makes
  visible whether one channel is silent (suggesting either I don't use
  it or its scanner pattern needs work).

Tests:
- 7 new tests (source_kind field round-trip; CLI integration for both
  correction and claim; no-trigger-on-neutral-content guards).
- 20/20 tracker tests pass; 31/31 multiplex + tracker suite green.

Empirical verification: a correction filed mid-session about this very
wiring gap landed in the pending file tagged source_kind='correction'.
The pattern self-dogfooded.

Co-Authored-By: Claude Opus 4.7 (1M context) <noreply@anthropic.com>
